A late-night meeting between eThekwini Municipality leadership and Durban taxi owners averted a taxi protest. On Monday, Yusuf Khaliva, deputy chairperson of the eThekwini Metro Taxi Council, announced that all taxis under their associations would not be working on Tuesday. ALSO READ | Commuters warned as Durban taxis set to stay off the roads on Tuesday in protest This was due to the “unfair” impounding of their taxis by eThekwini Metro Police, he said. However, on Monday night, Khaliva told The Witness that he met with the City's leadership and called the strike off. “We managed to resolve all issues with the mayor and metro police,” he said. “We are going to be working.” On Tuesday morning, taxis in the City were operating as normal.